# MR Review — Findings Protocol

## Finding format

Every finding uses this structure. No prose paragraphs.

```
### Finding: <short title>
- **File:** `path/to/file.ts`
- **Line:** <number or range — omit if uncertain>
- **Severity:** critical | high | medium | low | info
- **Category:** <persona/subcategory> (e.g., security/injection, compliance/vara-4.3)
- **Reference:** <regulation §, ADR number, CWE-ID, or incident ID>
- **Confidence:** <0.0–1.0> (lower if brain flagged prior false positive)
- **Message:** <what's wrong and why — one sentence>
- **Suggestion:** <how to fix — one sentence or code snippet>
```

## Verdict

After all findings, produce:

```
## Review Summary (<persona>)
- **Findings:** <count by severity>
- **Verdict:** APPROVE | REQUEST_CHANGES | BLOCK
- **Rationale:** <1-2 sentences>
```

| Condition | Verdict |
|-----------|---------|
| Any `critical` | BLOCK |
| Any `high` | REQUEST_CHANGES |
| Only `medium` / `low` / `info` | APPROVE (with comments) |

## Posting to GitLab

- Inline discussions on diff lines for findings with line numbers
- Summary note with the verdict table after all personas complete
- Check existing MR discussions first — never duplicate

## Integrity rules

- Never approve code you didn't analyze — read the full diff
- Never fabricate line numbers — use file-level finding if unsure
- Never invent regulation sections — cite only real references
- State what you don't know — if a file is outside your expertise, say so
- Respect brain: if brain says "false positive", suppress unless new evidence contradicts
